{"timestamp": "2026-05-26 17:36:46,334", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.validation", "module": "logging_config", "function": "log_validation_result", "line": 185, "message": "{\"timestamp\": \"2026-05-26T17:36:46.333939\", \"task_id\": \"unknown\", \"task_objective\": \"Implement module to analyze job description and extract required skills, responsibilities, and criteria\", \"result\": \"```python\\nimport re\\n\\ndef analyze_job_description(job_description: str):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"Analyzes the job description text and extracts required skills, responsibilities, and criteria sections.\\n    Returns a dictionary with three keys: 'skills', 'responsibilities', and 'criteria', each containing a list of strings.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    # Define section headings and regex patterns\\n    section_patterns = {\\n        'skills': r'(?:required skills|skills required|skills|technical skills):?\\\\\\\\s*(.*?)(?=\\\\\\\\n{2,}|\\\\Z)',\\n    ...\", \"validation_type\": \"text\", \"status\": \"completed\", \"feedback\": \"here are some feedbacks:\\n- The docstring states the function returns a dictionary, but the implementation returns a tuple of three lists. This should be made consistent.\\n- The regex patterns over-escape backslashes (`\\\\\\\\s`, `\\\\\\\\n`, `\\\\\\\\Z`) in raw strings; they should be single backslashes (`\\\\s`, `\\\\n`, `\\\\Z`).\\n- Duplicate items may arise (especially in fallback); it’s better to deduplicate results.\\n- It’s helpful to annotate the return type for clarity.\\n\\nhere are the changes:\\n```python\\nimport re\\nfrom typing import List, Tuple\\n\\ndef analyze_job_description(job_description: str) -> Tuple[List[str], List[str], List[str]]:\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Analyzes the job description text and extracts required skills, responsibilities, and criteria sections.\\n    Returns three lists of strings: (skills, responsibilities, criteria).\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    # Define section headings and regex patterns\\n    section_patterns = {\\n        'skills': r'(?:required skills|skills required|skills|technical skills):?\\\\s*(.*?)(?=\\\\n{2,}|$)',\\n        'responsibilities': r'(?:responsibilities|key responsibilities|job duties):?\\\\s*(.*?)(?=\\\\n{2,}|$)',\\n        'criteria': r'(?:requirements|qualifications|criteria|experience needed):?\\\\s*(.*?)(?=\\\\n{2,}|$)'\\n    }\\n    results = {'skills': [], 'responsibilities': [], 'criteria': []}\\n\\n    # Ensure the text ends with two newlines for lookahead\\n    text = job_description.strip() + \\\"\\\\n\\\\n\\\"\\n\\n    # Extract each section\\n    for section, pattern in section_patterns.items():\\n        match = re.search(pattern, text, re.IGNORECASE | re.DOTALL)\\n        if match:\\n            block = match.group(1).strip()\\n            # Split by line breaks or common bullet delimiters\\n            items = re.split(r'[\\\\n•\\\\-]+', block)\\n            for item in items:\\n                cleaned = item.strip(' *:;,.')\\n                if cleaned:\\n                    results[section].append(cleaned)\\n\\n    # Fallback keyword-based extraction for skills if none found\\n    if not results['skills']:\\n        keywords = [\\n            'Python', 'Java', 'JavaScript', 'C\\\\+\\\\+', 'C#', 'SQL', 'AWS',\\n            'React', 'Angular', 'Node\\\\.js', 'Machine Learning', 'Deep Learning',\\n            'Cloud Computing', 'Project Management', 'DevOps', 'Testing',\\n            'Data Analysis', 'Communication'\\n        ]\\n        for kw in keywords:\\n            if re.search(rf'\\\\b{kw}\\\\b', text, re.IGNORECASE):\\n                results['skills'].append(kw)\\n\\n    # Deduplicate while preserving order\\n    def dedupe(seq):\\n        seen = set()\\n        return [x for x in seq if not (x in seen or seen.add(x))]\\n\\n    skills = dedupe(results['skills'])\\n    responsibilities = dedupe(results['responsibilities'])\\n    criteria = dedupe(results['criteria'])\\n\\n    return skills, responsibilities, criteria\\n```\"}"}
{"timestamp": "2026-05-26 17:36:57,803", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.validation", "module": "logging_config", "function": "log_gpt_conversation", "line": 403, "message": "{\n  \"event_type\": \"gpt_conversation\",\n  \"task_id\": \"task_4\",\n  \"conversation_type\": \"task_execution\",\n  \"iteration\": 1,\n  \"messages\": [\n    {\n      \"role\": \"system\",\n      \"content\": \"\\n# Role:\\nHelp me produce a precise and detailed solution for the given task. Follow these instructions exactly:\\n\\n# Objective & Steps:\\n1. Ensure Completeness:\\n   - Avoid placeholders or incomplete text.\\n   - Your output must meet all requirements of the task.\\n   - Include all necessary details so that the output is self-contained and can be directly used as input for downstream tasks.\\n\\n2. Maintain Precision and Clarity:\\n   - Your output will be used as input for subsequent tasks; therefore, it must be comprehensive and precise.\\n   - **Output the answer only without any jusifications**\\n\\n3. Avoid Repetition:\\n   - Do not repeat verbatim any content from previous tasks.\\n   - Ensure your output is original and adds value to the workflow.\\n\\n\\n\\n# Audience:\\nYour output will be used as a solution for the given task, it will be used in the later validation and intergration process.\\n\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"user\",\n      \"content\": \"# **The Overall Goal**\\nYou are a workflow planning agent.\\nYour task is to:\\n-\\\"Analyze the job description\\\",\\n    \\\"Analyze the candidate resume\\\",\\n    \\\"Conduct technical interview\\\",\\n    \\\"Send emails as and when needed\\\",\\n    \\\"Score candidate responses\\\",\\n    \\\"Generate final evaluation report\\\"\\n\\nReturn the output as a Python list of strings.\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n---\\n# **Context from Upstream Tasks**\\nTask task0:\\n  Objective: Implement module to analyze job description and extract required skills, responsibilities, and criteria\\n  Result: ```python\\nimport re\\n\\ndef analyze_job_description(job_description: str):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"Analyzes the job description text and extracts required skills, responsibilities, and criteria sections.\\n    Returns a dictionary with three keys: 'skills', 'responsibilities', and 'criteria', each containing a list of strings.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    # Define section headings and regex patterns\\n    section_patterns = {\\n        'skills': r'(?:required skills|skills required|skills|technical skills):?\\\\\\\\s*(.*?)(?=\\\\\\\\n{2,}|\\\\Z)',\\n        'responsibilities': r'(?:responsibilities|key responsibilities|job duties):?\\\\\\\\s*(.*?)(?=\\\\\\\\n{2,}|\\\\Z)',\\n        'criteria': r'(?:requirements|qualifications|criteria|experience needed):?\\\\\\\\s*(.*?)(?=\\\\\\\\n{2,}|\\\\Z)'\\n    }\\n    results = {'skills': [], 'responsibilities': [], 'criteria': []}\\n\\n    # Normalize whitespace\\n    text = job_description + '\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n'\\n\\n    for section, pattern in section_patterns.items():\\n        match = re.search(pattern, text, re.IGNORECASE | re.DOTALL)\\n        if match:\\n            block = match.group(1).strip()\\n            # Split by lines or common delimiters\\n            lines = re.split(r'[\\\\\\\\n•\\\\\\\\-]+', block)\\n            for item in lines:\\n                item = item.strip(' :;,.').replace(\\\"*\\\", \\\"\\\")\\n                if item:\\n                    results[section].append(item)\\n\\n    # Fallback keyword-based extraction if sections are sparse or not found, focusing on skills\\n    if not results['skills']:\\n        keywords = ['Python', 'Java', 'communication', 'SQL', 'AWS', 'JavaScript', 'C++', 'C#', 'React', 'Angular', 'Node.js', 'Data Analysis', 'Machine Learning', 'Deep Learning', 'Cloud Computing', 'Project Management', 'Testing', 'DevOps'] # Expanded keyword list\\n        for kw in keywords:\\n            if re.search(r'\\\\\\\\b' + re.escape(kw) + r'\\\\\\\\b', text, re.IGNORECASE):\\n                results['skills'].append(kw)\\n\\n    return results['skills'], results['responsibilities'], results['criteria']\\n```\\nTask task1:\\n  Objective: Implement module to analyze candidate resume and map experience to job requirements\\n  Result: ```python\\n[\\n    \\\"Parse job description text to extract and structure requirements (skills, years, responsibilities).\\\",\\n    \\\"Normalize extracted job requirements (standardize terminology, handle synonyms and variants).\\\",\\n    \\\"Parse resume content (TXT, PDF) to plain text.\\\",\\n    \\\"Extract key resume elements: skills, experiences (with dates), education, and project descriptions.\\\",\\n    \\\"Normalize resume skills using the same taxonomy as job requirements.\\\",\\n    \\\"Perform exact match mapping between resume skills and job requirements.\\\",\\n    \\\"Perform semantic similarity matching (e.g., using word embeddings or pretrained language models) to catch related skills.\\\",\\n    \\\"For each requirement, collect all matching resume entries and quantify proficiency (years, project count, role level).\\\",\\n    \\\"Assign weights to job requirements based on importance from the job description.\\\",\\n    \\\"Calculate a per-requirement match score: weighted combination of exact and semantic match strengths.\\\",\\n    \\\"Aggregate per-requirement scores into an overall resume–job match score.\\\",\\n    \\\"Generate a detailed mapping report showing each job requirement, matched resume evidence, and individual scores.\\\",\\n    \\\"Highlight strengths (high-scoring requirements) and gaps (unmatched or low scores).\\\",\\n    \\\"Provide a JSON-serializable output with structured fields: requirements, matches, scores, overall_score.\\\",\\n    \\\"Log and store parsed data and final results for downstream processing.\\\"\\n]\\n```\\n\\nTask task2:\\n  Objective: Implement email sending module to dispatch notifications and interview invites\\n  Result: ```python\\nimport smtplib\\nfrom email.message import EmailMessage\\nfrom typing import List, Dict\\n\\nclass EmailSender:\\n    def __init__(self, smtp_server: str, smtp_port: int, username: str, password: str, use_tls: bool = True):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Initialize the email sender with SMTP server details.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        self.smtp_server = smtp_server\\n        self.smtp_port = smtp_port\\n        self.username = username\\n        self.password = password\\n        self.use_tls = use_tls\\n\\n    def send_email(self, recipient: str, subject: str, body: str) -> bool:\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Sends a single email. Returns True if successful, False otherwise.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        try:\\n            msg = EmailMessage()\\n            msg[\\\"From\\\"] = self.username\\n            msg[\\\"To\\\"] = recipient\\n            msg[\\\"Subject\\\"] = subject\\n            msg.set_content(body)\\n\\n            with smtplib.SMTP(self.smtp_server, self.smtp_port) as server:\\n                if self.use_tls:\\n                    server.starttls()\\n                server.login(self.username, self.password)\\n                server.send_message(msg)\\n            print(f\\\"Email sent to {recipient} with subject '{subject}'\\\")\\n            return True\\n        except Exception as e:\\n            print(f\\\"Failed to send email to {recipient}: {e}\\\")\\n            return False\\n\\n    def send_notification(self, recipients: List[str], notification_subject: str, notification_body: str) -> Dict[str, bool]:\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Send a generic notification email to multiple recipients.\\n        Returns a dict mapping each recipient to True/False based on success.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        results = {}\\n        for email in recipients:\\n            success = self.send_email(email, notification_subject, notification_body)\\n            results[email] = success\\n        return results\\n\\n    def send_interview_invite(self, candidate_email: str, candidate_name: str, interview_date: str, instructions: str) -> bool:\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Send an interview invitation to a single candidate.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        subject = f\\\"Interview Invitation for {candidate_name}\\\"\\n        body = (\\n            f\\\"Hello {candidate_name},\\\\n\\\\n\\\"\\n            f\\\"You are invited to an interview on {interview_date}.\\\\n\\\"\\n            f\\\"Instructions:\\\\n{instructions}\\\\n\\\\n\\\"\\n            \\\"Please reply to confirm your availability.\\\\n\\\\n\\\"\\n            \\\"Best regards,\\\\n\\\"\\n            \\\"Recruitment Team\\\"\\n        )\\n        return self.send_email(candidate_email, subject, body)\\n\\n# Example usage\\nif __name__ == \\\"__main__\\\":\\n    smtp_config = {\\n        \\\"smtp_server\\\": \\\"smtp.example.com\\\",\\n        \\\"smtp_port\\\": 587,\\n        \\\"username\\\": \\\"recruiter@example.com\\\",\\n        \\\"password\\\": \\\"securepassword\\\",\\n        \\\"use_tls\\\": True\\n    }\\n\\n    email_sender = EmailSender(**smtp_config)\\n\\n    # Send a generic notification\\n    notifications = email_sender.send_notification(\\n        recipients=[\\\"applicant1@example.com\\\", \\\"applicant2@example.com\\\"],\\n        notification_subject=\\\"Application Received\\\",\\n        notification_body=\\\"Thank you for applying. We have received your application and will be in touch.\\\"\\n    )\\n    print(\\\"Notification results:\\\", notifications)\\n\\n    # Send an interview invite\\n    invite_success = email_sender.send_interview_invite(\\n        candidate_email=\\\"candidate@example.com\\\",\\n        candidate_name=\\\"Jane Doe\\\",\\n        interview_date=\\\"2024-07-01 10:00 AM\\\",\\n        instructions=\\\"Please join the Zoom meeting with the link provided in the calendar invite.\\\"\\n    )\\n    print(\\\"Interview invite sent:\\\", invite_success)\\n```\\n\\n\\n---\\n# **Downstream Tasks Objectives**\\nTask task4:\\n  Objective: Implement scoring module to evaluate candidate responses against criteria\\n\\n---\\n# **Current Task Requirements**\\nImplement technical interview conductor module to present questions and capture responses\\n\\n---\\n\\n# **Required Output Format**\\nPython code\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"gpt_response\": \"```python\\nclass TechnicalInterviewConductor:\\n    def __init__(self, questions):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Initializes the interview conductor with a list of questions.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        self.questions = questions\\n        self.responses = {}\\n\\n    def present_question(self, question_number):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Presents a question to the candidate and captures the response.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        if 1 <= question_number <= len(self.questions):\\n            question = self.questions[question_number - 1]\\n            print(f\\\"Question {question_number}: {question}\\\")\\n            response = input(\\\"Your answer: \\\")  # Capture response via console input\\n            self.responses[question] = response\\n            return True\\n        else:\\n            print(\\\"Invalid question number.\\\")\\n            return False\\n\\n    def get_response(self, question):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Returns the candidate's response to a specific question.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        return self.responses.get(question, None)\\n\\n    def conduct_interview(self):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Conducts the entire interview, presenting each question sequentially.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        for i in range(1, len(self.questions) + 1):\\n            self.present_question(i)\\n\\n    def get_all_responses(self):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Returns all captured responses as a dictionary.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        return self.responses\\n\\n# Example Usage\\nif __name__ == \\\"__main__\\\":\\n    sample_questions = [\\n        \\\"Explain the concept of polymorphism in object-oriented programming.\\\",\\n        \\\"Describe the difference between a stack and a queue.\\\",\\n        \\\"What are the advantages of using a relational database?\\\",\\n        \\\"How does garbage collection work in Python?\\\",\\n        \\\"Explain the concept of recursion and provide an example.\\\"\\n    ]\\n\\n    interviewer = TechnicalInterviewConductor(sample_questions)\\n    interviewer.conduct_interview()\\n\\n    all_responses = interviewer.get_all_responses()\\n    print(\\\"\\\\nAll Responses:\\\")\\n    for question, answer in all_responses.items():\\n        print(f\\\"Question: {question}\\\\nAnswer: {answer}\\\\n\\\")\\n```\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-26T17:36:57.803249\"\n}"}
